        "text": "The document outlines procedures for the registration and qualification of market participants, specifically focusing on the interconnection of new or amended generation resources. \n\n1. **Paragraph (3) Replacement**: \n   - ERCOT must receive a Standard Generation Interconnection Agreement (SGIA) or a letter from a Municipal Utility or Electric Cooperative.\n   - ERCOT evaluates if the proposed Generation Resource, Energy Storage Resource (ESR), Synchronous Generation (SOG), or Settlement Only Self-Generator (SOESS) meets Planning Guide requirements.\n   - ERCOT reviews the proposal to ensure it doesn't violate operational standards.\n   - ERCOT must provide its determination to the Transmission Service Provider (TSP) and the resource owner within 90 days.\n   - ERCOT's determination does not prevent future actions if standards are violated.\n\n2. **Paragraph (4) Replacement**:\n   - An Interconnecting Entity (IE) cannot proceed with initial synchronization if:\n     - ERCOT determines potential violations of operational standards.\n     - Planning Guide Section 5.3.5 requirements are incomplete.\n     - Required Subsynchronous Resonance (SSR) studies and protections are not completed and approved.\n\nThese changes ensure compliance with operational standards and proper evaluation before synchronization.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_16:_Registration_and_Qualification_of_Market_Participants/page_27.jpg",
          "page_num": 27,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 16: Registration and Qualification of Market Participants",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "afd06272-a4b2-4ee7-b211-6348b972e83d",
        "score": 0.6025606,
        "text": "The document discusses interzonal congestion in the ERCOT electricity market, highlighting its economic impact. Congestion occurs when lower-cost power cannot be delivered due to constrained interfaces, necessitating the use of higher-cost resources. ERCOT manages this by setting clearing prices for energy in each zone, with the price difference between zones representing the congestion cost. Market participants can hedge these costs using Transmission Congestion Rights (TCRs) or Pre-assigned Congestion Rights (PCRs), which provide payments corresponding to the congestion price. TCRs are obtained through auctions, while PCRs are allocated based on historical usage. The document also reviews the allocation of TCRs and PCRs for each Congestion Management System (CSC) in 2003, with reference to a figure showing average allocations and SPD-modeled flows.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2003/page_124.jpg",
          "page_num": 124,
          "title": "2003 State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Wholesale Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2003,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "eff82a96-0453-4502-8343-e92e809243ff",
        "score": 0.5938436,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures for conducting Effective Load Carrying Capability (ELCC) studies and estimating firm peak loads for the ERCOT system:\n\n### ELCC Studies (Section 3.2.6.2)\n1. **Frequency and Purpose**: ERCOT will conduct ELCC studies every three years or as needed, based on resource and generation technology trends. These studies assess the capability of resources to meet demand.\n   \n2. **Standards and Tools**: The studies will adhere to the Public Utility Commission of Texas (PUCT) standards and use Monte Carlo simulations to determine ELCC values.\n\n3. **Scope**: The studies will calculate average ELCCs for Wind Generation Resources (WGRs), Photovoltaic Generation Resources (PVGRs), and Energy Storage Resources (ESRs) by reserve risk period and resource region.\n\n4. **Output**: The studies will produce a range of ELCC values for different resource mixes and forecasts over the next five years.\n\n### Firm Peak Load Estimates (Section 3.2.6.3)\n1. **Annual Forecasting**: ERCOT will annually forecast total hourly loads for at least ten future years using econometric models, considering weather, demographics, and other factors.\n\n2. **Equation**: The firm peak load and net load estimates are calculated using a specific equation that accounts for various resource and reserve factors.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of these studies and forecasts in ensuring reliable electricity supply and planning for future resource needs.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_71.jpg",
          "page_num": 71,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "2ca5586f-6835-4c90-8b95-0b9ddf3b4a7d",
        "score": 0.5937037,
        "text": "The document discusses the ERCOT process for establishing congestion rights in the transmission system. It compares actual and allowable flow for the West to North CSC, noting that actual flow was often below the limit by an average of 81 MW. The section focuses on the Congestion Rights Market, explaining how ERCOT allocates and sells transmission congestion rights. \n\nERCOT conducts summer planning studies to determine interface capabilities under peak conditions, which form the basis for 40% of the rights sold annually. The remaining 60% are based on monthly updates. Monthly studies are more accurate for real-time conditions, but they can still be affected by unexpected outages or planned outages unknown during summer studies. This can lead to discrepancies between actual and modeled flows, requiring ERCOT to adjust flow limits.\n\nThe document also mentions that prior to 2005, 60% of estimated capability was sold annually, but this changed due to discrepancies in capability estimates. The quantities of Pre-assigned Congestion Rights (PCRs) and annual Transmission Congestion Rights (TCRs) are consistent across months.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2007/page_140.jpg",
          "page_num": 140,
          "title": "2007 State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Wholesale Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2007,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f3a72755-4f57-4589-9d5f-60a942687564",
        "score": 0.5921841,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the ERCOT system, focusing on management activities and approval requirements for certain types of work. \n\n1. **NPRR857 Conditions**: \n   - Southern Cross must provide ERCOT with funds to cover the project's estimated cost.\n   - An interconnection agreement must be signed with a Transmission Service Provider (TSP).\n   - ERCOT must receive written notice from the TSP that Southern Cross has provided notice to proceed with construction and financial security for the interconnection facilities.\n\n2. **Energizing New Facilities**:\n   - Before energizing or placing new or relocated facilities into service, entities must enter information into the Outage Scheduler and receive written approval from ERCOT.\n\n3. **Types of Work Requiring ERCOT Approval**:\n   - Coordination with ERCOT is required for any addition, replacement, change, or removal of:\n     - Transmission lines\n     - Equipment like circuit breakers, transformers, and reactive devices\n     - Resource interconnections\n     - Protection and control schemes, including changes to Remedial Action Plans (RAPs), SCADA systems, and Energy Management Systems.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_79.jpg",
          "page_num": 79,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6ce6f62e-4b2e-4567-bd97-17e7c903f737",
        "score": 0.59121245,
        "text": "The document discusses the process of improving consistency between congestion rights and actual transmission flows in ERCOT. It highlights the importance of aligning predicted and real-time outages to enhance the accuracy of congestion rights availability. Currently, ERCOT evaluates these rights 35 days before the auction month, which may allow for discrepancies due to unforeseen outages. The document suggests that conducting evaluations closer to the auction date could improve accuracy.\n\nIt also references a New York ISO provision from 2004 aimed at reducing inconsistencies by estimating flow reductions due to unaccounted outages, charging lost congestion rents to transmission owners, and encouraging better maintenance scheduling.\n\nThe section on the Congestion Rights Market explains ERCOT's method for determining and auctioning congestion rights. ERCOT uses summer transmission planning studies to allocate 40% of congestion rights in an annual auction, with the remaining 60% based on monthly updates. This approach aims to better reflect actual conditions and improve market efficiency.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2005/page_154.jpg",
          "page_num": 154,
          "title": "2005 State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Wholesale Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2005,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "96cc2687-fb56-49ba-8aae-234530e48187",
        "score": 0.5906203,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures for evaluating and responding to proposed resource outages within the ERCOT system:\n\n### Evaluation of Proposed Resource Outage (3.1.6.5)\n1. **Violation of Reliability Standards**: If a proposed outage, combined with existing ones, risks violating reliability standards, ERCOT must:\n   - Communicate with the requesting Qualified Scheduling Entity (QSE) as per the Resource Outage Rejection Notice.\n   - Investigate Constraint Management Plans (CMPs) to address security violations and optimize transmission usage.\n   - Consider modifying previous approvals of transmission facilities or resource outages based on their impact on the ERCOT system.\n\n2. **Transmission Security**: If security can be maintained using alternatives, ERCOT may direct these alternatives and approve the proposed outage.\n\n3. **Rejection of Outage**: If security issues remain unresolved despite alternatives, ERCOT will reject the proposed outage.\n\n### Timelines for Response by ERCOT for Resource Planned Outages (3.1.6.6)\n1. **Approval/Rejection Timelines**: ERCOT must approve or reject outage requests based on the following schedule:\n   - **Three days lead time**: Approve/reject by 1800 hours, two days before the outage.\n   - **Four to eight days lead time**: Approve/reject by 1800 hours, three days before the outage.\n   - **Nine to 15 days lead time**: Approve/reject four days before the outage.\n   - **16 to 45 days lead time**: Approve/reject within five business days after submission.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_37.jpg",
          "page_num": 37,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

steps.content:
{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "\"Full Interconnection Study\" \"FIS\" \"interconnection application\" fee schedule",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "ERCOT",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "d1db4316-6cd7-4f00-aa3a-acaf1c0c62a1",
        "score": 0.53747404,
        "text": "The document is a fee schedule from ERCOT effective October 1, 2024. It outlines various application and inspection fees related to energy generation and transmission services. Key points include:\n\n1. **Full Interconnection Study (FIS) Application Fee**: \n   - $3,000 for new generators.\n   - $2,700 for modifications to existing generators.\n\n2. **Qualified Scheduling Entity (QSE) and Related Fees**:\n   - $500 per entity for QSE, Sub-QSE, Competitive Retailer (CR), Congestion Revenue Right (CRR) Account Holder, Independent Market Information System Registered Entity (IMRE), Resource Entity, and Transmission/Distribution Service Providers (TDSPs).\n\n3. **Counter-Party Background Check Fee**:\n   - $350 per principal.\n\n4. **Weatherization Inspection Fees**:\n   - Resource Entities and Transmission Service Providers must pay fees for weatherization inspections as per Texas Administrative Code \u00a7 25.55.\n\nThe document specifies that fees are associated with modifications based on the cumulative megawatt (MW) amount of changes submitted within the last 12 months. If modifications are less than 10 MW, the fee is $2,300; if 10 MW or greater, the fee is $14,000.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_3.jpg",
          "page_num": 3,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c2995e81-75a7-4720-be2c-3b3782fec3d4",
        "score": 0.433492,
        "text": "The document is an ERCOT fee schedule effective October 1, 2024. It outlines various fees related to ERCOT services, which are non-refundable unless specified by ERCOT Protocols.\n\n1. **Private Wide Area Network (WAN) Fees**:\n   - Based on actual costs for procuring, using, maintaining, and connecting to third-party networks for ERCOT WAN communications.\n   - Initial installation or reconfiguration costs capped at $7,000.\n   - Monthly network management fee capped at $450.\n\n2. **ERCOT Load Resource Registration and Generator Interconnection or Modification Fees**:\n   - $500 for registering a new Load Resource.\n   - Additional $500 if increasing MW size by more than 20% or changing registration type.\n   - Generator registration fees:\n     - $2,300 for Settlement Only Distribution Generators (SODGs).\n     - $8,000 for generators under 10 MW.\n     - $14,000 for generators 10 MW or greater.\n   - $8,000 for changing an existing SODG to a Distribution Generation Resource (DGR).\n\nThe document provides specific fee amounts and conditions for various registration and modification scenarios.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_2.jpg",
          "page_num": 2,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ea4afbdd-d2af-4ff9-83d4-7c9ed39e1395",
        "score": 0.41207963,
        "text": "The document outlines inspection fees and related costs for Transmission Service Providers (TSPs) and Resource Entities associated with the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT). Key points include:\n\n1. **Inspection Fees**: \n   - TSPs must pay $4,500 for each inspected substation or switching station.\n   - Resource Entities, excluding federally owned ones, pay fees based on their MW capacity relative to aggregate capacity, calculated semiannually.\n\n2. **Calculation and Invoicing**:\n   - ERCOT calculates fees twice a year, using MW capacity data from the last 15 business days of the period.\n   - Invoices are issued semiannually in January and July, with a 30-day payment deadline. Late payments incur 18% annual interest and are reported to the Public Utility Commission of Texas.\n\n3. **Additional Fees**:\n   - Voluminous copy fee: $0.15 per page over 50 pages.\n   - Information request costs: Actual costs estimated by ERCOT, requiring pre-approval and payment by the requester.\n   - ERCOT labor costs: $15 per hour for information requests deemed burdensome.\n\nThese fees and processes are part of ERCOT's regulatory framework to ensure compliance and operational readiness.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_4.jpg",
          "page_num": 4,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "053fa2ca-d2c1-45b6-81d8-5697777eb760",
        "score": 0.40418658,
        "text": "The document outlines the ERCOT System Administration and User Fees as part of the settlement and billing process.\n\n### ERCOT System Administration Fee\n1. **Authorization and Purpose**: The Public Utility Commission of Texas (PUCT) authorizes ERCOT to charge this fee to fund its budget. The fee is converted into a charge for each Qualified Scheduling Entity (QSE) using a specified formula.\n   \n2. **Posting and Approval**: ERCOT must post the fee on its website. Any changes approved by PUCT must be posted within two business days, including the effective date.\n\n3. **Calculation**: Each QSE pays the fee for every 15-minute Settlement Interval. The formula provided is:\n   \\[\n   \\text{ESACAMT}_q = \\text{LAFF} \\times \\max(0, \\sum \\text{RTAML}_{q,p})\n   \\]\n   - **ESACAMT\\(_q\\)**: The fee for each QSE per interval.\n   - **RTAML\\(_{q,p}\\)**: Real-Time Adjusted Metered Load for each Settlement Point.\n   - **LAFF**: Load Administration Fee Factor.\n   - **q**: A QSE.\n   - **p**: A Settlement Point.\n\n### User Fees\n1. **Approval and Application**: The ERCOT Board approves user fees for services provided to Market Participants or other entities. These fees are set according to Board Policies and Procedures and may include costs for applications, WAN, and interconnection studies.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_51.jpg",
          "page_num": 51,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1fd3717b-8871-4b24-8078-2cb06232d7bf",
        "score": 0.39896554,
        "text": "The document outlines the process for collecting a fee from Retail Electric Providers (REPs) who assign customers to a non-ERCOT sponsored load profile segment. This is mandated by P.U.C. SUBST. R. 25.131, which requires ERCOT to establish a method for compensating the original requester of a new profile segment and notifying Distribution Service Providers (DSPs) authorized to use it.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Fee Collection Process**: ERCOT must implement a process to collect fees from REPs for non-ERCOT sponsored profile segments.\n\n2. **Cost Documentation**: Within 30 days of ERCOT's final approval of a profile segment request, the requester must submit documentation of incurred costs. These costs must be directly related to the profile segment change request and incurred no earlier than 24 months before the original submission date.\n\n3. **Recoverable Costs**: \n   - Costs for load research paid to DSPs or ERCOT, including buying and installing Interval Data Recorders (IDRs), communication equipment, and meter reading.\n   - Reasonable third-party costs, with documentation, for defining, preparing, and reviewing the request.\n   - Internal documented costs detailing personnel, hours, and expenses related to the request.\n\nThe process ensures transparency and accountability in the development of new load profile segments.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_55.jpg",
          "page_num": 55,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1f526825-afca-4438-a778-5ae11f9e07bd",
        "score": 0.3820526,
        "text": "The document page is from Section 5: Transmission Security Analysis and Reliability Unit Commitment of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, dated February 1, 2025. It details startup and operational costs for various power generation configurations.\n\n1. **Startup Costs**:\n   - **Simple Cycle \u2265 90 MW**: $5,000 for cold, intermediate, and hot startups.\n   - **Combined Cycle**: Costs are the sum of individual unit costs within the configuration.\n     - Combustion turbine < 90 MW: $2,300 for all startup types.\n     - Combustion turbine \u2265 90 MW: $5,000 for all startup types.\n     - Steam turbine: Costs decrease from $3,000 (cold) to $1,250 (hot).\n     - Gas-steam non-reheat boiler: Costs decrease from $2,310 (cold) to $866.25 (hot).\n     - Gas-steam reheat boiler: Costs decrease from $3,000 (cold) to $1,125 (hot).\n     - Gas-steam supercritical boiler: Costs decrease from $4,800 (cold) to $1,800 (hot).\n     - Nuclear, coal, lignite, and hydro: Costs decrease from $7,200 (cold) to $2,700 (hot).\n     - Renewable: Not applicable.\n\n2. **Variable O&M Costs**:\n   - Simple cycle \u2265 90 MW: $3.94/MWh.\n   - Combined cycle: $3.19/MWh.\n   - Gas-steam non-reheat, reheat, and supercritical boilers: $7.08/MWh.\n   - Nuclear, coal, lignite, and hydro: $5.02/MWh.\n   - Renewable: $5.50/MWh.\n\n3. **O&M Cost Reduction**:\n   - For 2012, standard O&M costs are reduced by 10% from the specified levels.\n\n4. **Resource Category Costs for 2009**:\n   - Aeroderivative simple cycle: $900 for all startup types, $3.55/MWh for variable O&M.\n   - Reciprocating Engine: $52.20/MW based on seasonal net max sustainable ratings, $4.58/MWh for variable O&M.\n   - Simple cycle < 90 MW: $2,070 for all startup types, $3.55/MWh for variable O&M.\n   - Simple cycle \u2265 90 MW: $4,500 for all startup types, $3.55/MWh for variable O&M.\n   - Combined cycle: Costs vary by unit type within the configuration.\n   - Gas-steam non-reheat and reheat boilers: Costs decrease from $2,079 (cold) to $779.63 (hot), $6.37/MWh for variable O&M.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_5:_Transmission_Security_Analysis_and_Reliability_Unit_Commitment/page_30.jpg",
          "page_num": 30,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 5: Transmission Security Analysis and Reliability Unit Commitment",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "cf42e3e5-ca5c-43e1-a923-5111f220d123",
        "score": 0.3812967,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2002 Annual Report\" by the Market Oversight Division of the Public Utility Commission of Texas. It includes two main sections:\n\n1. **Figure 17: 2002 Local Congestion Costs by Area**\n   - A table and bar graph display local congestion costs across various areas in Texas for 2002, totaling $160.49 million. The areas listed include DFW ($44.37 million), North ($26.78 million), Valley ($19.61 million), and others, with Houston having the lowest cost at $1.17 million.\n\n2. **Section D: ERCOT Uplift**\n   - This section explains the process of allocating costs to Qualified Scheduling Entities (QSEs) based on loads and exports within the ERCOT region. The total uplift was $118.8 million in 2001 and increased to $277.2 million in 2002. The uplift includes local congestion costs, Local Balancing Energy Service Charge, OOMC and OOME costs, and RMR contracts.\n   - A table (Table 10) details ERCOT administration fees and uplift costs by month for 2002, showing various charges such as Balancing Energy Neutrality Adjustment and Local Balancing Energy Service Charge.\n   - It notes that in August 2001, high uplift charges for BENA were experienced, but after a zonal congestion assignment in February 2002, BENA charges were reduced. However, other charges like the Local Balancing Energy Service Charge increased significantly in late 2002.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2002/page_40.jpg",
          "page_num": 40,
          "title": "2002 Annual Report on The ERCOT Wholesale Market",
          "year": 2002,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "be692b41-e152-4a12-86f6-5f333c2acd5d",
        "score": 0.37602735,
        "text": "The document page is from the 2002 Annual Report by the Market Oversight Division of the Public Utility Commission of Texas. It discusses local congestion costs and ERCOT uplift charges.\n\n### Local Congestion Costs:\n- Totaled about $212 million over the first 17 months of the market, with $25.9 million in 2001 and $186.3 million in 2002.\n- The OOME Down costs allowed market participants to exploit local constraints using the \"DEC\" game, where they submit schedules that would cause congestion, get paid to resolve it, and socialize the costs.\n- A table and graph show monthly local congestion costs, peaking in July 2002 at $47.85 million.\n- Specific areas like the DFW Area and the Wind Area near McCamey, Texas, saw significant congestion, with the DFW Area's costs rising from 3.5% in 2001 to 27.6% in 2002.\n- Discussions are ongoing to reduce congestion uplift from wind resources by eliminating OOME Down payments and issuing tradable transmission rights.\n\n### ERCOT Uplift:\n- Uplift charges were $118.8 million in 2001 and $277.2 million in 2002, including administrative fees.\n- The increase in 2002 was due to high BENA charges and significant rises in charges for Local Balancing Energy Service, OOME, OOM Capacity, and Reliability-Must-Run services.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2002/page_11.jpg",
          "page_num": 11,
          "title": "2002 Annual Report on The ERCOT Wholesale Market",
          "year": 2002,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "5db85b18-d957-4966-905b-4bc8062d53b4",
        "score": 0.3730834,
        "text": "The document page outlines specific fees related to ERCOT services:\n\n1. **Requests**: If a request requires ERCOT employee or contractor time, an estimate of labor costs will be provided. The requestor must approve and pay these costs before receiving the information.\n\n2. **ERCOT Training Fees**: Courses that award Continuing Education Hours (CEHs) cost $25 per North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) CEH. Examples include the Operator Training Seminar and Black Start Training.\n\n3. **Cybersecurity Monitor Fee**: This fee for non-ERCOT utilities participating in the Texas Cybersecurity Monitor Program varies annually. The current fee is available on ERCOT's website.\n\nThe document is part of the ERCOT Fee Schedule effective October 1, 2024.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_5.jpg",
          "page_num": 5,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c9f4953b-d4cf-427b-90b5-fb5e568953d6",
        "score": 0.36877114,
        "text": "The document is a page from the 2002 Annual Report of the Market Oversight Division, focusing on the ERCOT Administration Fee and Uplift Costs. It includes a table detailing monthly costs from July 2001 to December 2002, with categories such as Balancing Energy Neutrality Adjustment, Black Start Capacity Charge, and others, culminating in a total of $396,027,458.\n\nThe text discusses \"Congestion Rights,\" which began in February 2002. These rights are financial instruments allowing market participants to hedge against congestion costs. The document explains the allocation and auctioning of Transmission Congestion Rights (TCRs) and Pre-assigned Congestion Rights (PCRs), noting that 60% of TCRs are awarded annually and 40% monthly. The total TCR auction revenue was $91.1 million, with credit payments of $22.5 million, resulting in a net revenue of $68.7 million.\n\nThe section on \"Market Issues\" addresses overscheduling and BENA (Balancing Energy Neutrality Adjustment). It highlights how the costs for relieving zonal congestion were distributed among market participants, incentivizing them to schedule generation across congested areas to receive higher payments.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2002/page_12.jpg",
          "page_num": 12,
          "title": "2002 Annual Report on The ERCOT Wholesale Market",
          "year": 2002,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

