      {
        "id": "cf42e3e5-ca5c-43e1-a923-5111f220d123",
        "score": 0.3812967,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2002 Annual Report\" by the Market Oversight Division of the Public Utility Commission of Texas. It includes two main sections:\n\n1. **Figure 17: 2002 Local Congestion Costs by Area**\n   - A table and bar graph display local congestion costs across various areas in Texas for 2002, totaling $160.49 million. The areas listed include DFW ($44.37 million), North ($26.78 million), Valley ($19.61 million), and others, with Houston having the lowest cost at $1.17 million.\n\n2. **Section D: ERCOT Uplift**\n   - This section explains the process of allocating costs to Qualified Scheduling Entities (QSEs) based on loads and exports within the ERCOT region. The total uplift was $118.8 million in 2001 and increased to $277.2 million in 2002. The uplift includes local congestion costs, Local Balancing Energy Service Charge, OOMC and OOME costs, and RMR contracts.\n   - A table (Table 10) details ERCOT administration fees and uplift costs by month for 2002, showing various charges such as Balancing Energy Neutrality Adjustment and Local Balancing Energy Service Charge.\n   - It notes that in August 2001, high uplift charges for BENA were experienced, but after a zonal congestion assignment in February 2002, BENA charges were reduced. However, other charges like the Local Balancing Energy Service Charge increased significantly in late 2002.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2002/page_40.jpg",
          "page_num": 40,
          "title": "2002 Annual Report on The ERCOT Wholesale Market",
          "year": 2002,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
