      {
        "id": "3f904d22-d2ca-4207-86e8-b77cfe7c073e",
        "score": 0.40961152,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the ERCOT system, focusing on the construction and management of interconnections. Key points include:\n\n1. **Coordination and Consistency**: ERCOT, TSPs, DCTOs, and Resource Entities must coordinate to ensure that Transmission Elements are consistently defined across operational models.\n\n2. **Unique Identifiers**: Each Transmission Element must have a unique identifier, following a naming convention developed with input from TSPs and approved by the Technical Advisory Committee (TAC). ERCOT will provide details of all Transmission Elements to Market Participants daily.\n\n3. **Southern Cross Requirements**: Southern Cross must provide ERCOT with notice and financial security to proceed with interconnection construction. They must also cover the entire project cost and have an agreement with a TSP.\n\n4. **Non-Operational Changes**: If a TSP submits a NOMCR for non-operational changes, ERCOT will implement the request.\n\nThe document includes specific amendments (NPRR857) to ensure Southern Cross meets financial and procedural conditions for interconnection projects.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_173.jpg",
          "page_num": 173,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0822d091-fb54-4495-ad5b-dcd3c33afc88",
        "score": 0.37536,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures for the registration and qualification of market participants, specifically focusing on the interconnection of new or amended generation resources. \n\n1. **Paragraph (3) Replacement**: \n   - ERCOT must receive a Standard Generation Interconnection Agreement (SGIA) or a letter from a Municipal Utility or Electric Cooperative.\n   - ERCOT evaluates if the proposed Generation Resource, Energy Storage Resource (ESR), Synchronous Generation (SOG), or Settlement Only Self-Generator (SOESS) meets Planning Guide requirements.\n   - ERCOT reviews the proposal to ensure it doesn't violate operational standards.\n   - ERCOT must provide its determination to the Transmission Service Provider (TSP) and the resource owner within 90 days.\n   - ERCOT's determination does not prevent future actions if standards are violated.\n\n2. **Paragraph (4) Replacement**:\n   - An Interconnecting Entity (IE) cannot proceed with initial synchronization if:\n     - ERCOT determines potential violations of operational standards.\n     - Planning Guide Section 5.3.5 requirements are incomplete.\n     - Required Subsynchronous Resonance (SSR) studies and protections are not completed and approved.\n\nThese changes ensure compliance with operational standards and proper evaluation before synchronization.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_16:_Registration_and_Qualification_of_Market_Participants/page_27.jpg",
          "page_num": 27,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 16: Registration and Qualification of Market Participants",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "21978cbb-2b1a-47d6-b6f0-7d9d511da1be",
        "score": 0.37112075,
        "text": "The document outlines a schedule and process for submitting and updating information related to the ERCOT (Electric Reliability Council of Texas) system. It includes a table with deadlines for various stages of model updates:\n\n1. **Deadlines**: Specifies dates for submitting information to ERCOT, completing models for testing, and updating network operations models for production.\n\n2. **Process Steps**:\n   - **Model Completion**: Models must be complete and available for testing by specified dates.\n   - **Testing Completion**: Updated network operations models must be tested and completed by certain dates.\n   - **Production Environment Update**: Models are updated in the production environment by specific deadlines.\n   - **Target Physical Equipment**: Indicates the month when physical equipment is included in the production model.\n\n3. **Notes**:\n   - Submissions must follow the NOMCR process or other ERCOT-prescribed processes.\n   - Data changes and fidelity tests are conducted using the Network Operations Model test facility.\n   - Testing involves market participants and TSPs (Transmission Service Providers) before production.\n   - Updates include changes within the same month, with load dates published by ERCOT.\n\n4. **Resource Registration**: Resource entities must submit complete initial registration data for inclusion in the operations model by specified deadlines, as per ERCOT's guidelines.\n\nThis structured process ensures timely updates and testing of network operations models within the ERCOT system.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_161.jpg",
          "page_num": 161,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "2659f5c0-0bac-4506-8127-decc0d598db3",
        "score": 0.36881706,
        "text": "The document outlines the transition processes for ESI IDs in the Texas retail electric market, managed by ERCOT. It describes two main processes:\n\n1. **Mass Transition Process**:\n   - Initiated when ESI IDs need to be transitioned in bulk due to business circumstances.\n   - ERCOT submits an 814_03 Enrollment Notification Request for meter reads, two days after initiating the transition.\n   - If actual meter reads are unavailable, estimates may be used.\n   - The TDSP responds with an 814_04 transaction and other necessary responses within two business days.\n   - ERCOT monitors transitioned ESI IDs for 60 days, ending upon the first completed switch or move.\n\n2. **Acquisition Transfer Process**:\n   - Used when ESI IDs are transferred due to acquisition.\n   - Similar to the mass transition, ERCOT submits an 814_03 request for meter reads.\n   - Estimated meter reads may be used if actual reads are unavailable.\n\nBoth processes involve specific transaction codes and timelines, with detailed responsibilities outlined in the Retail Market Guide.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_15_-_Customer_Registration/page_10.jpg",
          "page_num": 10,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 15 - Customer Registration",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "5aaa88da-104f-4bb2-90ee-78004ef68a37",
        "score": 0.35847417,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures for data acquisition and aggregation from ERCOT-Polled Settlement Metered Entities. \n\n### Key Sections:\n\n#### 11.1 Overview\n- ERCOT collects interval data from EPS metered entities using the Meter Data Acquisition System (MDAS).\n- The data is validated, edited, estimated, adjusted, netted, loss corrected, split, and aggregated for settlement inputs.\n\n#### 11.1.2 ERCOT Polled Settlement Meter Data Collection\n- ERCOT remotely interrogates EPS metered entities to gather necessary data for settlement.\n- The MDAS verifies the meter\u2019s Interval Data Recorder (IDR) protocol and device identifier.\n- If remote polling fails, ERCOT collaborates with Transmission Service Providers (TSP) and Distribution Service Providers (DSP) to resolve issues within the timeframe specified in Section 10.\n\n#### 11.1.3 ERCOT Polled Settlement Meter Time Synchronization\n- ERCOT updates the clock of any EPS meter outside the defined threshold.\n- TSP and DSP assist in correcting timekeeping inconsistencies within the specified timeframe.\n\n#### 11.1.4 ERCOT Polled Settlement Meter Data Validation, Editing, and Estimation\n- After synchronization and data retrieval, ERCOT validates the data.\n- Validation includes flagging intervals with missing data and exception reporting if zero values exceed tolerance limits.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_11:_Data_Acquisition_and_Aggregation/page_4.jpg",
          "page_num": 4,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 11: Data Acquisition and Aggregation",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9b9e2171-956c-4a3c-a2f5-c523655d6889",
        "score": 0.3560182,
        "text": "The document page is from the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, specifically Section 3, which deals with management activities for the ERCOT system. It outlines procedures for handling changes and updates to the Transmission Element and Network Operations Model.\n\n1. **Transmission Element Changes (Paragraph 5)**: ERCOT is responsible for correcting errors found during testing due to inaccurate information submissions. Each Transmission Service Provider (TSP), Direct Current Transmission Operator (DCTO), and Resource Entity must provide accurate information initially.\n\n2. **Interim Model Updates (Paragraph 6)**: ERCOT can update the model on an interim basis outside the standard timeline for correcting configuration changes or errors, such as those caused by storms. Notices of changes are communicated electronically to all market participants and posted on the MIS Secure Area.\n\n3. **Unintentional Inconsistencies (Paragraph 7)**: Interim updates may be necessary due to unintentional inconsistencies between the model and the physical grid. ERCOT will report these changes to the PUCT Staff and the Independent Market Monitor (IMM) and provide notice to market participants.\n\n4. **Validation of Network Operations Model (Paragraph 8)**: TSPs and Resource Entities, with ERCOT's help, must validate their portion of the Network Operations Model according to a specified timeline. ERCOT provides TSPs access to the model and real-time state estimator results for analysis and validation.\n\n5. **NPRR857 Amendments**: The document includes amendments (NPRR857) that replace paragraphs 5 and 8, contingent upon Southern Cross providing ERCOT with funds for the project and signing an interconnection agreement with a TSP. The TSP must notify ERCOT of Southern Cross's notice to proceed with construction and provide financial security for the interconnection facilities.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_167.jpg",
          "page_num": 167,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7161b4eb-0cbe-4c19-afab-bc4f7baf2bf4",
        "score": 0.3517943,
        "text": "The document page discusses interzonal congestion within the ERCOT electricity market, focusing on intervals when interzonal constraints were binding. It highlights the importance of these intervals for market performance. Figure 51 illustrates the average SPD-calculated power flows between the four ERCOT zones during constrained periods for six Commercially Significant Constraints (CSCs). The arrows indicate the average magnitude and direction of these flows, with the frequency of constraints shown in parentheses. The flows are as follows:\n\n- West Zone to North Zone: 250 MW (254 intervals)\n- North Zone to West Zone: 373 MW (424 intervals)\n- North Zone to South Zone: 232 MW (105 intervals)\n- South Zone to Houston Zone: 903 MW (452 intervals)\n- Houston Zone to North Zone: 851 MW (1476 intervals)\n\nThe numbers in parentheses represent the total number of constrained settlement intervals for each CSC.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2007/page_127.jpg",
          "page_num": 127,
          "title": "2007 State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Wholesale Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2007,
          "market": "ERCOT",
