      },
      {
        "id": "6c78dbb9-1136-4860-b0c6-283eaaa6dda1",
        "score": 0.34367877,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to bill payment switch holds and invoicing between Transmission and/or Distribution Service Providers (TDSP) and Competitive Retailers (CR) in the context of retail point-to-point communications.\n\n### 24.1.3.2 Bill Payment Switch Hold\n1. **Definition**: A bill payment switch hold is applied when a customer enters a payment agreement with their current CR. This hold is placed on the ESI ID as per regulatory standards.\n2. **Adding a Switch Hold**:\n   - The CR sends a 650_01 Service Order Request to the TDSP to add the hold.\n   - The TDSP responds with a 650_02 Service Order Response, confirming receipt.\n   - Completion confirmation is received through an 814_20 ESI ID Maintenance Request.\n3. **Removing a Switch Hold**:\n   - The CR sends a 650_01 request to remove the hold.\n   - The TDSP responds with a 650_02, confirming receipt.\n   - Completion confirmation is received through an 814_20 transaction.\n\n### 24.2 Transmission and/or Distribution Service Provider to Competitive Retailer Invoice\n1. **810_02 TDSP Invoice**:\n   - May include various charges for the billing period.\n   - After validation, the CR has five business days to respond to any rejections.\n   - If no response is received, the CR must use approved market processes to resolve issues.\n2. **Transaction Limits**:\n   - Only one 810_02 transaction per service period is allowed, with exceptions for late payment charges.\n3. **Pairing with 867_03**:\n   - The 810_02 can be paired with an 867_03 to trigger the customer billing process.\n4. **Rebilling**:\n   - The TDSP may cancel and replace an 810_02 transaction, with the replacement becoming the monthly invoice.",
        "metadata": {
